# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: almere
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Games saw 10,625 athletes compete, some 600 more than expected, accompanied by 5,501 team officials from 201 countries, with 301 medal events in 28 different sports.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Athens became the fourth city to host the Summer Olympic Games on two occasions (together with Paris, London and Los Angeles).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A new medal obverse was introduced at these Games, replacing the design by Giuseppe Cassioli that had been used since 1928.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The new design features the Panathenaic Stadium in Athens rectifying the long-running mistake of using a depiction of the Roman Colosseum rather than a Greek venue.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Olympic Games were hailed as "unforgettable dream games" by then-IOC president Jacques Rogge, and left Athens with a significantly improved infrastructure, including a new airport, ring road and subway system.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] There has been debate (mostly in popular media) regarding the cost of the Games and their possible contribution to the 2010–18 Greek government-debt crisis, although there is little or no evidence supporting this claim.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Games were generally deemed to be a success, with the rising standard of competition amongst nations across the world.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The final medal tally was led by the United States, followed by China and Russia with host nation Greece in 15th place.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Several world and Olympic records were also broken during these Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Chile, Chinese Taipei, Dominican Republic, Georgia and Israel won their first Olympic gold medals.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Eritrea and Paraguay won their first Olympic medals.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The United Arab Emirates (UAE) won both their first Olympic medal and gold medal in this event.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Athens was chosen as the host city during the 106th IOC Session held in Lausanne, Switzerland, on 5 September 1997.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Greek capital had lost its bid to organize the 1996 Summer Olympics to the American city of Atlanta nearly seven years before, during the 96th IOC Session in Tokyo, Japan on 18 September 1990.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Under the direction of Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, Athens pursued another bid, this time for the right to host the Summer Olympics in 2004.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Unlike the 1996 bid that was seen arrogant when the city was bidding, the 2004 bid was lauded for its low scale, humility, honest and earnestness, its focused message, and a more real and detailed bid concept.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] During the unsuccessful 1996 bid, concerns and criticisms were raised – primarily regarding critical subjects about the city's infrastructural readiness, its air pollution, its budget and politicization of the Games' events and their preparations.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Another factor that contributed to the Greek capital's selection was a growing sentiment among some IOC members to restore some original values of the Olympics to the Modern Games, a component which they felt was lost during the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After leading all voting rounds, Athens easily defeated Rome in the fifth and final vote.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cape Town, Stockholm, and Buenos Aires (the latter won the rights to host the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics in 2013), the three other cities that made the IOC shortlist, were eliminated in prior rounds of voting.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Six other cities submitted applications, but their bids were dropped by the IOC in 1996.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] These cities were Istanbul, Lille, Rio de Janeiro (the latter won the rights to host the 2016 Summer Olympics in 2009), San Juan, Seville, and Saint Petersburg.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Summer Olympic Games cost the Government of Greece near €9 billion to stage.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Athens 2004 Organizing Committee (ATHOC), responsible for the preparation and organisation of the Games, concluded its operations as a company in 2005 with a surplus of €130.6 million.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The State's contribution to the total ATHOC budget was 8% of its expenditure against an originally anticipated 14%.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The overall revenue of ATHOC, including income from tickets, sponsors, broadcasting rights, merchandise sales etc., totalled near €2.1 billion.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The largest percentage of that income (38%) came from media rights.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] According to the cost-benefit evaluation of the impact of the Athens 2004 Olympic Games presented to the Greek Parliament in January 2013 by the Minister of Finance Mr.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Giannis Stournaras, the overall net economic benefit for Greece was positive.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Greek Ministry of Finance reported in 2013 that the expenses of the Greek state for the Athens 2004 Olympic and Paralympic Games, including both infrastructure and organizational costs, reached the amount of €8.5 billion.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The same report further explains that €2 billion of this amount was covered by the revenue of the ATHOC (from tickets, sponsors, broadcasting rights, merchandise sales etc.) and that another €2 billion was directly invested in upgrading hospitals and preserving archaeological sites.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Therefore, the net infrastructure costs related to the preparation of the Athens 2004 Olympic Games was €4.5 billion, substantially lower than the reported estimates, and mainly included long-standing fixed asset investments in numerous municipal and transport infrastructures.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] On the revenue side, the same report estimates that incremental tax revenues of approximately €3.5 billion arose from the increased activities caused by the Athens 2004 Olympic Games during the period 2000 to 2004.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] These tax revenues were paid directly to the Greek state specifically in the form of incremental social security contributions, income taxes and VAT tax paid by all the companies, professionals, and service providers that were directly involved with the Olympic Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cost per sporting event for Athens 2004 was US$9.8 million.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This compares with US$14.9 million for Rio 2016, US$49.5 million for London 2012, and US$22.5 million for Beijing 2008.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Average cost per event for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$19.9 million.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cost per athlete for Athens 2004 was US$0.3 million.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This compares with US$0.4 million for Rio 2016, US$1.4 million for London 2012, and US$0.6 million for Beijing 2008.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Average cost per athlete for the Summer Games since 1960 is US$0.6 million.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Cost overrun for Athens 2004 was 49%, measured in real terms from the bid to host the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This compares with 51% for Rio 2016 and 76% for London 2012.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Average cost overrun for the Summer Games since 1960 is 176%.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] By late March 2004, some Olympic projects were still behind schedule, and Greek authorities announced that a roof it had initially proposed as an optional, non-vital addition to the Aquatics Center would no longer be built.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The main Olympic Stadium, the designated facility for the opening and closing ceremonies, was completed only two months before the Games opened.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This stadium was completed with a retractable glass roof designed by Spanish architect Santiago Calatrava.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The same architect also designed the Velodrome and other facilities.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Infrastructure, such as the tram line linking venues in southern Athens with the city centre, and numerous venues were considerably behind schedule just two months before the start of the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The subsequent pace of preparation, however, made the rush to finish the Athens venues one of the tightest in Olympics history.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Greeks, unperturbed, maintained that they would make it all along.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] By July/August 2004, all venues were delivered: in August, the Olympic Stadium was officially completed and opened, joined or preceded by the official completion and openings of other venues within the Athens Olympic Sports Complex (OAKA), and the sports complexes in Faliro and Helliniko.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Late July and early August witnessed the Athens Tram become operational, and this system provided additional connections to those already existing between Athens city centre and its waterfront communities along the Saronic Gulf.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The upgrades to the Athens Metro were also completed, and the new lines became operational by mid-summer.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] EMI released *Unity*, the official pop album of the Athens Olympics, in the leadup to the Olympics.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It features contributions from Sting, Lenny Kravitz, Moby, Destiny's Child, and Avril Lavigne.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] EMI has pledged to donate US$180,000 from the album to UNICEF's HIV/AIDS program in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] At least 14 people died during the work on the facilities.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Most of these people were not from Greece.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Before the Games, Greek hotel staff staged a series of one-day strikes over wage disputes.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] They had been asking for a significant raise for the period covering the event being staged.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Paramedics and ambulance drivers also protested.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] They claimed to have the right to the same Olympic bonuses promised to their security force counterparts.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Panorama of Athens Olympic Sports Complex.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The lighting ceremony of the Olympic flame took place on 25 March 2004 in Ancient Olympia.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time ever, the flame travelled around the world in a relay to various Summer Olympic host cities (past and future) and other large cities, before returning to Greece.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Athens Olympic Broadcasting served as the host broadcaster for the Games, providing over 35,000 hours of coverage to over 300 television channels around the world.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Local rights to the Games were held by ERT which devoted their three channels (ET1, NET and ET3) to more than 24 hours of Olympic coverage.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time, major broadcasters were allowed to serve video coverage of the Olympics over the Internet, provided that they restricted this service geographically, to protect broadcasting contracts in other areas.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee forbade Olympic athletes, as well as coaches, support personnel and other officials, from setting up specialized weblogs or other websites for covering their personal perspective of the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] They were not allowed to post audio, video, or photos that they had taken.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] An exception was made if an athlete already has a personal website that was not set up specifically for the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] NBC launched its own Olympic website, NBCOlympics.com.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Focusing on the television coverage of the Games, it did provide video clips, medal standings, live results.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Its main purpose, however, was to provide a schedule of what sports were on the many stations of NBC Universal.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were shown on television 24 hours a day, on one network or another.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medals awarded during the 2004 Summer Olympics introduced a redesigned obverse for Olympic medals, marking the first major change to the standard design since the 1928 Summer Olympics.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Organizers stated that the redesign was intended to emphasize the Greek heritage of the Olympic Games and their revival in the modern era.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Previous Olympic medals, used from 1928 through the 2000 Summer Olympics, depicted the goddess Nike seated while holding an ear of corn and a wreath.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For Athens 2004, Nike was instead portrayed flying into the stadium to deliver victory to the winning athlete.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Panathenaic Stadium, the venue of the first modern Olympic Games in 1896, was also depicted on the obverse side, alongside an engraving identifying the athlete’s sporting discipline.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medals were designed by Elena Votsi and produced by Efsimon.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medals had a diameter of 60 millimetres and were awarded in gold, silver and bronze compositions corresponding to first, second and third place respectively.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The podiums used during the 2004 Summer Olympics incorporated elements of the “Panorama” visual identity developed for the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The “Panorama” design reflected aspects of Greek culture, language and landscape, drawing inspiration from the colours of the sea and the tones of the country’s olive groves.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] During the 2004 Summer Olympics, medal-winning athletes standing on the podium were crowned with olive wreaths, referencing traditions associated with the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] As with any enterprise, the Organizing Committee and everyone involved with it relied heavily on technology in order to deliver a successful event.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] ATHOC maintained two separate data networks, one for the preparation of the Games (known as the Administrative network) and one for the Games themselves (Games Network).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] This infrastructure was created and maintained to serve directly more than 150,000 ATHOC Staff, Volunteers, Olympic family members (IOC, NOCs, Federations), Partners & Sponsors and Media.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It also kept the information flowing for all spectators, TV viewers, Website visitors and news readers around the world, prior and during the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Media Center was located inside the Zappeion which is a Greek national exhibition center.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Between June and August 2004, the technology staff worked in the Technology Operations Center (TOC) from where it could centrally monitor and manage all the devices and flow of information, as well as handle any problems that occurred during the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Systems, Telecommunications, Information Security, Data Network, Staffing, etc.) under a TOC Director and corresponding team leaders (Shift Managers).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The TOC operated on a 24x7 basis with personnel organized into 12-hour shifts.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony of the games, directed by choreographer Dimitris Papaioannou and produced by Jack Morton Worldwide, led by project director David Zolkwer, was held on 13 August 2004.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It began with a twenty-eight (the number of the Olympiads up to then) second countdown paced by the sounds of an amplified heartbeat.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] As the countdown was completed, fireworks rumbled and illuminated the skies overhead.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After a drum corps and bouzouki players joined in an opening march, the video screen showed images of flight, crossing southwest from Athens over the Greek countryside to ancient Olympia.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Then, a single drummer in the ancient stadium joined in a drum duet with a single drummer in the main stadium in Athens, joining the original ancient Olympic Games with the modern ones in symbolism.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of the drum duet, a single flaming arrow was launched from the video screen (symbolically from ancient Olympia) and into the reflecting pool, which resulted in fire erupting in the middle of the stadium creating a burning image of the Olympic rings rising from the pool.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Opening Ceremony was a pageant of traditional Greek culture and history hearkening back to its mythological beginnings.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The program began as a young Greek boy sailed into the stadium on a 'paper-ship' waving the host nation's flag to aethereal music by Manos Hatzidakis and then a centaur appeared, followed by a gigantic head of a cycladic figurine which eventually broke into many pieces symbolising the Greek islands.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Underneath the cycladic head was a Hellenistic representation of the human body, reflecting the concept and belief in perfection reflected in Greek art.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A man was seen balancing on a hovering cube symbolising man's eternal 'split' between passion and reason followed by a couple of young lovers playfully chasing each other while the god Eros was hovering above them.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] There followed a very colourful float parade chronicling Greek history from the ancient Minoan civilization to modern times.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Also, lower frontal nudity of men dressed as ancient Greek statues was shown in such a way that the area below the waist was cut off by the bottom of the screen.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Overall, NBC's coverage of the Olympics has been praised, and the company was awarded with 6 Emmy Awards for its coverage of the Games and technical production.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, NBC televised all 28 sports in the 2004 Games, becoming the first broadcaster to do so.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Following the artistic performances, a parade of nations entered the stadium with over 10,500 athletes walking under the banners of 201 nations.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The nations were arranged according to Greek alphabet making the Philippines, Finland, Fiji, Chile, and Hong Kong the last five to enter the stadium before the Greek delegation.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] On this occasion, in observance of the tradition that the delegation of Greece opens the parade and the host nation closes it, the Greek flag bearer opened the parade and all the Greek delegation closed it.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Based on audience reaction, the emotional high point of the parade was the entrance of the delegation from Afghanistan which had been absent from the Olympics and had female competitors for the first time.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Iraqi delegation also stirred emotions.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Also recognized was the symbolic unified march of athletes from North Korea and South Korea under the Korean Unification Flag.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The country of Kiribati made its debut appearance at these Games and East Timor made a debut under its own flag.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After the Parade of Nations, during which the Dutch DJ Tiësto provided the music, the Icelandic singer Björk performed the song "Oceania", written specially for the event by her and the poet Sjón.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony culminated in the lighting of the Olympic cauldron by 1996 gold medalist windsurfer Nikolaos Kaklamanakis.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Many key moments in the ceremony, including the lighting of the Olympic Cauldron, featured music composed and arranged by New Zealand composer John Psathas.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The gigantic cauldron, which was styled after the Athens 2004 Olympic torch, pivoted down to be lit by the 35-year-old, before slowly swinging up and lifting the flame above the stadium.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Following this, a fireworks display commenced to conclude the ceremony.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] All National Olympic Committees (NOCs) except Djibouti participated in the Athens Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Two new NOCs had been created since 2000 and made their debut at these Games (Kiribati and East Timor).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Therefore, with the return of Afghanistan (who had been banned from the 2000 Summer Olympics), the number of participating nations increased from 199 to 201.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Additionally, Yugoslavia had changed its name the year prior to Serbia and Montenegro and its code from YUG to SCG; the country would dissolve two years later, making this its only Olympics appearance under the new moniker.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Georgia's new flag made its debut at the Olympics by unfurling it at the opening ceremony on 13 August.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] It replaces the post-Soviet flag, which had been used since Lillehammer 1994.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] In the table below, the number in parentheses indicates the number of participants contributed by each NOC.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] 10,557 athletes from 201 NOCs participated in the 2004 Summer Olympics.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The sports featured at the 2004 Summer Olympics are listed below.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Officially there were 301 events in 28 sports as swimming, diving, synchronised swimming and water polo are classified by the IOC as disciplines within the sport of aquatics, and wheelchair racing was a demonstration sport.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time, the wrestling category featured women's wrestling and in the fencing competition women competed in the sabre.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] American Kristin Heaston, who led off the qualifying round of women's shot put became the first woman to compete at the ancient site of Olympia.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The demonstration sport of wheelchair racing was a joint Olympic/Paralympic event, allowing a Paralympic event to occur within the Olympics, and for the future, opening up the wheelchair race to the able-bodied.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The 2004 Summer Paralympics were also held in Athens, from 17 to 28 September.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Games were concluded on 29 August 2004.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The closing ceremony was held at the Athens Olympic Stadium, where the Games had been opened 16 days earlier.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Around 70,000 people gathered in the stadium to watch the ceremony.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The initial part of the ceremony interspersed the performances of various Greek singers, and featured traditional Greek dance performances from various regions of Greece (Crete, Thessaly, etc.).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The event was meant to highlight the pride of the Greeks in their culture and country for the world to see.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A significant part of the closing ceremony was the exchange of the Olympic flag of the Athens Games between the mayor of Athens and the mayor of Beijing, host city of the next Olympics.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After the flag exchange a presentation from the Beijing delegation presented a glimpse into Chinese culture for the world to see.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The medal ceremony for the last event of the Olympics, the men's marathon, was conducted, with Stefano Baldini from Italy as the winner.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The bronze medal winner, Vanderlei Cordeiro de Lima of Brazil, was simultaneously announced as a recipient of the Pierre de Coubertin Medal for his bravery in finishing the race despite being attacked by a rogue spectator while leading with 7 km to go.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A flag-bearer from each nation's delegation then entered along the stage, followed by the competitors *en masse* on the floor.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] All of them were led by Pyrros Dimas (weightlifter) and Liu Xiang (hurdler).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Short speeches were presented by Gianna Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, President of the Organising Committee, and by President Dr.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Jacques Rogge of the IOC, in which he described the Athens Olympics as "unforgettable, dream Games".
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Rogge had previously declared he would be breaking with tradition in his closing speech as President of the IOC and that he would never use the words of his predecessor Juan Antonio Samaranch, who used to always say 'these were the best ever games'.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The national anthems of Greece and China were played in a handover ceremony as both nations' flags were raised.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Mayor of Athens, Dora Bakoyianni, passed the Olympic Flag to the Mayor of Beijing, Wang Qishan.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] After a short cultural performance by Chinese actors, dancers, and musicians directed by eminent Chinese director Zhang Yimou, Rogge declared the 2004 Olympic Games closed.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] The Olympic flag was next raised again on 10 February 2006 during the opening ceremony of the next Winter Olympics in Torino.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] A young Greek girl, 10-year-old Fotini Papaleonidopoulou, lit a symbolic lantern with the Olympic Flame and passed it on to other children before "extinguishing" the flame in the cauldron by blowing a puff of air.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] These are the top ten nations that won medals in the 2004 Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p01] Facilities of the 2004 Summer Olympics in the Greater Athens area.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Mascots have been a tradition at the Olympic Games since the 1968 Winter Olympics in Grenoble, France.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The 2004 Olympics had two official mascots: *Athena* and *Phevos* (Greek pronunciation: Athina and Fivos).
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The sister and brother were named after Athena, the goddess of wisdom, strategy and Phoebus, the god of light and music, respectively.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] They were inspired by the ancient daidala, which were toy dolls that also had religious connotations.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] To commemorate the 2004 Olympics, a series of Greek high value euro collectors' coins were minted by the Mint of Greece, in both silver and gold.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The pieces depict landmarks in Greece as well as ancient and modern sports on the obverse of the coin.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] On the reverse, a common motif with the logo of the Games, circled by an olive branch representing the spirit of the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Preparations to stage the Olympics led to a number of positive developments for the city's infrastructure.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] All of the above infrastructure is still in use to this day, and there have been continued expansions and proposals to expand Athens' metro, tram, suburban rail and motorway network, the airport, as well as further plans to pedestrianize more thoroughfares in the historic center of Athens.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] As of 2012 many conversion schemes have stalled owing to the Greek government-debt crisis, though many of these facilities are now under the control of domestic sporting clubs and organizations or the private sector.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] The Hellinikon Olympic Complex saw multiple venues demolished and the park is being transformed into Hellinikon Metropolitan Park which will become home to Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Athens, the first integrated resort in Greece.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] There have been arguments (mostly in popular media) that the cost of the 2004 Athens Summer Games was a contributor to the Greek government-debt crisis that started in 2010, while a lot of focus has been on the use of the facilities after the Games.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Furthermore, the aforementioned arguments do not even take into account the profits (direct and indirect) generated by the Games, which may well have surpassed the above costs.
[src:almere/2004-summer-olympics-p02] Finally, popular arguments about "rotting" of many of the facilities, appear to ignore the actual utilization of many of these structures.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held in the Netherlands on 7 March 2006.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] About 11.8 million people could vote in 419 municipalities.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Due to municipal reorganisations, 15 municipalities held elections in January 2006 and 24 municipalities held elections in November 2006.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In some cities, such as Amsterdam, there were two elections, for the municipality and for the borough councils.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Official results were announced on 9 March 2006.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The Labour Party (PvdA) obtained the most votes and seats, more than recovering from the losses of the 2002 elections.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The Socialist Party (SP) almost doubled in size, partly due to its participation in more municipalities than in 2002.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA), the People's Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD) and the Democrats 66 (D66) all had noticeable losses, which may in part have been caused by dissatisfaction with the national government, of which they are the coalition partners.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Overall, local parties of the Leefbaar type lost out as well after some success during the previous elections.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Although the above shows the total results for the whole of the Netherlands, this has no official effect on national politics.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] It is often seen as an indication for it, but the issues and the parties that participate at the two levels do not always coincide.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] For example, SP got almost twice as many seats because they participated in almost twice as many municipalities as it did in 2002, which will in part explain their success, but even so, they still did not participate in all municipalities, so not everyone could vote for them.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] This is fairly similar to the election results and a confirmation of polls showing a possible majority for the three left-wing parties, which would be a first in the Netherlands and may be a reaction to what they call the present 'right-wing winter'.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The 'forgotten winner' (who received little media attention) was Christian Union (CU), which was allied with Reformed Political Party (SGP) in many municipalities, but represented the winning part with 420 seats (SGP has always had a very steady following).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Leader André Rouvoet now said that this alliance might no longer be a good idea because the CU increased its vote share precisely in those places where SGP refused an alliance because the CU had a woman on its candidate list.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The SGP's attitude towards women was believed to reflect badly on the CU.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In keeping with their left-wing Christian nature, the CU was most successful in a band across the Netherlands that starts in the south west and largely coincides with the Bible Belt, but ends in the heavily socialist north east.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] As D66 focussed on local issues in its campaigns but suffered further losses, a common occurrence when the party participates in government.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In 2005, D66 minister Alexander Pechtold had proposed moving the elections in some municipalities to different years in order to reduce the influence of national politics, but this was opposed by the CDA.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Media attention before election day was manifested around Rotterdam, where the late Pim Fortuyn's Livable Rotterdam was a surprise winner in 2002, knocking the Labour Party (PvdA) out of the coalition for the first time since WWII.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] But now, PvdA even won more seats than it had before 2002, and became the largest party once again.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Livable Rotterdam came second and had already made clear it was not willing to enter into a coalition with the Labour Party, making the formation of a coalition difficult because all other parties are small (less than 10% of the vote).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In these 419 municipalities, percentages of over 30% were reached almost exclusively by the PvdA (in 64 municipalities, mostly in the northern provinces, especially Groningen and Friesland) and CDA (59 times, mostly in southern provinces).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Percentages over 40% were reached in 29 municipalities, again almost exclusively by PvdA (12) and CDA (10).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Absolute majorities (over 50%), which would not require a coalition, are a rarity in a parliamentary democracy with proportional representation and occurred only twice.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] PvdA won an absolute majority in Winschoten, Groningen with 49.7% of the votes and 9 out of 17 seats in the council, and CDA in Tubbergen, Overijssel province with 58.3% of the vote and 12 out of 19 seats in the council.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Half the people voted for the person at the top of the list.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] One third voted for someone they had met personally.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The enormous rise of SP in some municipalities presented several candidates with a problem because they have to take a seat in the council but could not combine it with their 'normal' jobs.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Polls showed a major shift in the issues.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In 2006, people mentioned employment, poverty, traffic, housing and education, largely the issues that left-wing parties focused on.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The issues of immigrant integration and safety, which had been important in 2002 and had led to the success of the Leefbaar parties, played a minor role this time.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In Nijmegen, with its all-left coalition, people's sense of safety had risen from 21% to 52% since that coalition came to power, illustrating that this is not just a right-wing issue.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The biggest shift among lower incomes was from the Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA) to the Socialist Party (SP), probably caused by the first two issues.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] A major issue in the campaign of the right-wing People's Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD) was to advise people not to vote for the PvdA.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] This was done in such a manner that PvdA leader Wouter Bos declared the VVD had been the best campaigner for the PvdA.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] He said about the VVD leader that "every time van Aartsen opens his mouth, we gain another seat".
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Voter turnout across the Netherlands was around 58%, slightly more than in the 2002 municipal elections.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Delfzijl was said to have the lowest turnout of the whole country, with 47.3% but this was due to 22% of the cast Delfzijl votes being blank, as a form of protest against the political mismanagement that entangled the city last year.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The Delfzijl turnout with the blank votes included was 61.1%.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The real lowest turnouts were in the major cities Eindhoven and The Hague, each with 47.5%.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The highest turnouts are traditionally in smaller communities and especially at the Wadden islands in the North.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The highest turnout this year was at Ameland with 87.3%.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] People of foreign origin (known in the Netherlands as allochtonen) constitute about 2.2 million of the constituency of 11.2 million.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Most are of German origin (320.000) and about half of non-western origin, most notably from Suriname (225.000) and Turkey (220.000).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Voter turnout among allochtones was higher than previously and many have voted PvdA.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] VVD parliamentary leader Jozias van Aartsen announced that since his party lost votes, while he had had high hopes to gain some (overall outcome for the VVD was less than 14% this time), he would retire from the leadership.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] He would remain in the House of Representatives.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Former party leader Hans Wiegel, who had hinted at returning to lead the party in the next general election announced he would not seek a return to politics.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] A likely candidate to succeed van Aartsen as political leader is Mark Rutte, the current staatssecretaris for higher education and science.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] He is seen as a representative for the more left-wing ('social liberal') side of VDD (although he himself denies this), illustrated by the fact that he does not wear a necktie, which, he says, illustrates that the VVD is for all people, not just an elite group.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] For the Christian Democratic Appeal an important part of the campaign was that regional and national politics are two separate things.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] For this reason, prime minister Balkenende did not participate (much) in the campaign and declared after the elections that the CDA would not change its national policy.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] D66 parliamentary leader Lousewies van der Laan remarked that this was the tenth election in a row (over 12 years) that D66 lost seats and that this time they would not seek the cause in external factors but within the party itself.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] People no longer knew what D66 stands for.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] An example was the wavering stance of D66 on the Afghanistan mission debates in December and January, first opposing it and then going along with it.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] There used to be a time limit to the duration of coalition talks, but that has been dropped, so the formations may take a long time.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] However, although this combination is close to 50% of the seats in many municipalities where all three participated, a majority is in most cases only just not possible or too narrow to be comfortable.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In Reiderland a non-left-wing council is not even possible.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] It is noteworthy that in Arnhem, that was often juxtaposed to nearby Nijmegen, such a coalition has now also become possible, although the existing very broad coalition hasn't lost its majority.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Another factor here is that the local branches confer with the national party because decisions at the two levels have to be harmonised.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Nationally, PvdA is doing well, but in some municipalities too left wing a coalition may not go down well with some people, which may have negative effects on PvdA during the 2007 national elections.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Also, local branches of a party may have a rather different signature from the local party, such as in Zaanstad, where the CDA is rather left wing.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] "They're called CDA, but that's where the similarity ends", according to a PvdA spokesman.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] And SP also differs strongly from place to place.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In some places they are considered decent politicians, in others too troublesome (SP used to lean towards Marxism and that may not have disappeared everywhere).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The subjects of housing and city renovation are often points of difference between PvdA and SP.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In Amsterdam, where this coalition would be biggest, SP have already left the talks, but PvdA and GroenLinks still have a majority of 27 out of 45 seats.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In Arnhem the three parties are talking but there are differences between PvdA and SP over how money should be spent (housing or redistribution).
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The Christian Union (CU) turned out to be very popular as a coalition partner, partly because their stance on social issues often coincides with that of the big winner PvdA, who led the coalition talks in most municipalities.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] Where PvdA and CDA form a coalition, they often took CU on board even when there was no need for a majority because, being both left-wing and Christian, they formed a bridge between those two parties.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] On 4 April CU had already entered a coalition in 21 new municipalities, whilst keeping its position in municipalities where they already were part of a coalition.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] They had won 12% more seats but their coalition-participation had risen by 69%.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] In Goes, the Christian parties CDA and SGP/CU formed a coalition with VVD on the day after the elections ("at record breaking speed"), without consulting the PvdA.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] This led to quite an uproar because it is customary that coalition talks are started by the biggest party, which was the PvdA.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] But what was really salient was that this was done on a Christian day of prayer for which the elections were shifted forward one day (elections are usually on Wednesdays) at the request of SGP, one of those new coalition partners.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] During inauguration hundreds gathered in front of the city hall, throwing eggs.
[src:almere/2006-dutch-municipal-elections] The new opposition demonstratively left the city hall after the inauguration and a VVD member almost attacked a protester.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held on Wednesday 3 March 2010 in most municipalities in the Netherlands.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] This election determined the composition of the municipal councils for the following four years.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] The elections were held a few weeks after the fall of the Fourth Balkenende cabinet.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] Nearly 24% of the vote went to local parties and independent candidates, more than any national political party.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] The Labour Party remained the most popular party overall, despite a significant decline in their vote share.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] Support for the CDA also decreased, while the VVD made moderate gains and Democrats 66 nearly doubled their support.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] The CDA held the most seats of any party, mainly due to its higher level of support in rural areas.
[src:almere/2010-dutch-municipal-elections] The Party for Freedom only contested the cities of Almere and The Hague, where it became the largest and second-largest party respectively.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held on 19 March 2014 in most municipalities in the Netherlands.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] This election determines the composition of the municipal councils for the following four years.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections are, unless exempted by an act of parliament, held every fourth year in the Netherlands as prescribed by the constitution.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] The previous municipal elections were held on 3 March 2010, the elections were originally planned for 5 March 2014.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Because this date coincided with Ash Wednesday, the elections were rescheduled to 19 March 2014.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] The elections were held in all municipalities, except those that were amalgamated in 2013 and 2014 or were intended to amalgamate in 2015.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Goeree-Overflakkee, Molenwaard and Schagen elected their councils late 2012; Alphen aan den Rijn, De Friese Meren, Heerenveen and Leeuwarden in November 2013; and 16 other municipalities will be involved in amalgamation and will have their elections in November 2014.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] There was some confusion among voters in these municipalities about these alternative dates.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] In the 2010 elections, local parties got 24% of the vote, with national parties taking most of the remaining seats.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Since then a general election was held in 2012 for the House of Representatives.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] In this election, the People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and Labour Party won a combined 79 out of 150 seats and formed a coalition government.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] These municipal elections were the first elections in the Netherlands since the new cabinet was formed.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] The Christian Democratic Appeal became the largest party nationally, earning 14% of the votes.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] D66 and SP also saw significant rises compared to the 2010 elections, getting 12% and 7% respectively.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] VVD, although still ranked third nationwide, lost significantly compared to the 2010 elections, winning 12% of the votes.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] The undisputed loser of the elections, however, was the PvdA, getting 10% of the votes and losing its plurality in Amsterdam, Rotterdam and The Hague.
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Geert Wilders's speech after the elections was widely seen as controversial because he led a chant at a rally after municipal elections last week, asking supporters in The Hague: "Do you want more or fewer Moroccans in this city and in the Netherlands?" The crowd chanted: "Fewer!
[src:almere/2014-dutch-municipal-elections] Fewer!", to which Wilders responded: "We'll take care of that.".
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held on 21 March 2018 in 335 municipalities in the Netherlands.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] The election coincided with the Intelligence and Security Services Act referendum.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] In the previous municipal elections, local political parties won by far most votes and seats.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Nationally, all local political parties won 28% of the votes and a third of municipal council seats.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Local parties have seen a steady rise since the 1990s.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] In 2018, Vlieland will be the only municipality in which no national political parties will contest the election.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Of all national political parties, the Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA) will contest most municipal elections; the party will be on the ballot in all but three (Rozendaal, Vlieland and Schiermonnikoog).
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] The Labour Party (PvdA) comes second, contesting over 320 elections, albeit on a joint list with allied parties in some municipalities.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] The People's Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD) will participate in over 315 elections, and the Democrats 66 in over 270, followed by GroenLinks in 220, the Christian Union in 169, the Socialist Party in 118 and the Reformed Political Party (SGP) in 99.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] The Party for Freedom (PVV), which had previously only participated in The Hague and Almere, initially planned to expand to a total of sixty municipalities, but has only been able to find suitable candidates in thirty, including Rotterdam.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] 50PLUS will expand to twenty municipalities, while the Party for the Animals (PvdD) will contest fifteen elections.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Two new national political parties will make their entrance to municipal politics.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Denk will contest the elections in fourteen municipalities, while the Forum for Democracy will only contest in Amsterdam.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Additionally, the latter has endorsed the local party Livable Rotterdam.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] 45 municipalities did not have elections on 21 March due to mergers.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal councils are elected using party-list proportional representation.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] The number of seats depends on the population of the municipality, ranging from nine seats for municipalities with a population below 3,000, to 45 seats for municipalities with a population over 200,000.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] After the 2018 municipal elections, the GroenLinks held the largest share of seats on the municipal council, though not enough to hold a majority.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] As no party held a majority, a left-leaning governing coalition was formed between GroenLinks, D66, the Labour Party, and the Socialist Party, which together hold 26 of the city's 45 council seats.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] The new city council elected Femke Halsema, a member of the GroenLinks, to be the mayor of Amsterdam.
[src:almere/2018-dutch-municipal-elections] Halsema is the first woman to be elected mayor of Amsterdam, as well as the first member of the GroenLinks to take that position.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held on 16 March 2022 in 333 municipalities in the Netherlands.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] In the previous municipal elections, local political parties won by far the most votes and seats.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Nationally, all local political parties won a total of 29% of the votes and around a third of municipal council seats.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Local parties have seen a steady rise since the 1990s and in Vlieland there are only local parties that participate.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Of all national political parties, the Christian Democratic Appeal (CDA) will contest the most municipal elections; the party will be on the ballot in all but five (Diemen, Ouder-Amstel, Rozendaal, Vlieland and Schiermonnikoog).
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] The People's Party for Freedom and Democracy (VVD) comes in second, contesting in 317 elections, while Democrats 66 participates in 289 elections.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] The Labour Party (PvdA) will participate in 303 elections, and GroenLinks in 229, many of which are joint lists between the two parties.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Meanwhile, the ChristianUnion runs in 175 and the Reformed Political Party (SGP) in 96, with these parties also having many joint lists.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] The Socialist Party participates in 86, Forum for Democracy (FvD), which had previously only participated in Amsterdam, has expanded significantly to participate in 50 elections.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] The Party for Freedom (PVV) participates in 31, Party for the Animals (PvdD) in 30, DENK in 20, 50PLUS in 19 and BIJ1 in 5.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] There are also 3 national parties participating for the first time in municipal elections, BvNL in 20 municipalities, Volt in 10, and JA21 only in Amsterdam.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Twelve municipalities did not have elections on 16 March due to mergers.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] All people above the age of 18, who are registered in a municipality, and have not been excluded from voting following a court's decision are eligible to vote.
[src:almere/2022-dutch-municipal-elections] Dutch citizenship is not required to be eligible to vote for municipal elections, non-EU nationals who have legally resided in the Netherlands for at least five years and EU citizens are also eligible to vote.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] Municipal elections were held on 18 March 2026 in 333 municipalities in the Netherlands.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] This election will determine the composition of the municipal councils for the following four years.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] During the 2026 municipal elections, at least eleven municipalities will be experimenting with a smaller ballot paper (A3 format).
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] These are Alphen aan den Rijn, Boekel, Gouda, 's-Hertogenbosch, Leiden, Meierijstad, Midden-Delfland, Nijmegen, Noordoostpolder, Soest and Tynaarlo.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] The municipality of Borne previously participated in the experiment, but decided not to participate in these elections due to concerns about the number of invalid votes and the reduced recognizability of candidates.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] Both the Ministry of the Interior and Kingdom Relations and the Electoral Council remain positive about the experiment, which should contribute to a simpler and faster voting and counting process.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] In the municipalities of Hilversum and Wijdemeren, redistricting elections will be held on 18 November 2026, if the parliamentary procedure regarding the merger bill is completed in time in 2026.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] The public bodies of Bonaire, Saba, and Sint Eustatius (Caribbean Netherlands) have many tasks that are performed by municipalities in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] However, the island council elections for these public bodies will take place simultaneously with the Provincial Council elections, which will be held for the first time in 2027.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] Due to irregularities involving proxy votes, the municipal council of Gorinchem voted to annul the results of the election.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] According to the NRC, voters (generally members of the Turkish minority) were coerced into giving away their voting passes and printed copies of their identity cards.
[src:almere/2026-dutch-municipal-elections] In the re-election, D66 lost a seat which was won by the CDA.
[src:almere/almere] Bordering Lelystad and Zeewolde, the municipality of Almere comprises six boroughs: Almere Stad (which is further split up into Almere Stad Oost, Almere Stad West and Almere Centrum), Almere Buiten, Almere Pampus (which is currently being designed), Almere Haven, Almere Hout and Almere Poort.
[src:almere/almere] Four of them feature official district or borough offices.
[src:almere/almere] Furthermore, the city also comprises the unofficial historic district and neighbourhood Oostvaardersdiep.
[src:almere/almere] Almere is part of the Amsterdam Metropolitan Area.
[src:almere/almere] Almere is the newest city in the Netherlands.
[src:almere/almere] The land on which the city was built, the Southern Flevoland polder, was reclaimed from the IJsselmeer from 1959 to 1968.
[src:almere/almere] The first house was constructed in 1976, and Almere became a municipality eight years later.
[src:almere/almere] The city is the eighth largest in the Netherlands, and it is the largest settlement in Flevoland by population with 229,574 inhabitants (CBS; 2025).
[src:almere/almere] In October 2007, the city council of Almere had made agreements with the government to expand the city to 350,000 inhabitants by 2030.
[src:almere/almere] The original plans for the IJsselmeerpolders saw the land being used for agriculture.
[src:almere/almere] This changed in the early 1960's according to the Dutch Central Bureau for Statistics.
[src:almere/almere] After World War II housing was needed for the rapidly growing population of Amsterdam and two towns were planned in the polders Oostelijk Flevoland and Zuidelijk Flevoland.
[src:almere/almere] The town in Oostelijk Flevoland became Lelystad.
[src:almere/almere] The town in Zuidelijk Flevoland was still called Zuidweststad (English: South West City) on the first sketches; but in the 1970s it became called *Almere*, named after the lake Almere, the early medieval name of the Zuiderzee.
[src:almere/almere] The first house in Almere was finished in 1976.
[src:almere/almere] At that time the town was still controlled by the *Openbaar Lichaam Zuidelijke IJsselmeerpolders* (Z.IJ.P.), with a Landdrost.
[src:almere/almere] In 1984 Almere became an official municipality, a year before the official establishment of its province, Flevoland.
[src:almere/almere] Originally, Almere was envisioned as a town with multiple centres.
[src:almere/almere] This idea was later abandoned in favour of allowing neighbourhoods like Tussen de Vaarten to be built.
[src:almere/almere] There is also a difference between the way houses are built in the oldest and the newest parts of the city.
[src:almere/almere] The housing plan in Almere in the 1970s was basic functionality and a levelling of social status.
[src:almere/almere] However, starting in the 1990s more exclusive homes with striking designs were built (notably in the Regenboogbuurt).
[src:almere/almere] Hein van der Loo (independent) has been mayor of Almere since March 2023, with the municipal council consisting of a coalition of several parties.
[src:almere/almere] The first municipal council was installed on 2 January 1984 in the presence of the then-Minister of the Interior Koos Rietkerk.
[src:almere/almere] The council elections took place on 21 September 1983.
[src:almere/almere] This *Adviesraad* was made up of different political parties similar to a local council.
[src:almere/almere] On 11 March 1977 the first *adviescommissie* was elected.
[src:almere/almere] It consisted of 5 people that were chosen on personal title.
[src:almere/almere] Since 2018, the council of Almere has comprised a total of 45 members.
[src:almere/almere] Almere is located in the polder of Southern Flevoland (Dutch: *Zuidelijk Flevoland*).
[src:almere/almere] It is the most western municipality of the province Flevoland.
[src:almere/almere] It borders with Markermeer in the west and north, Lelystad in the northeast, Zeewolde in the east, and Gooimeer in the south.
[src:almere/almere] Almere consists of three boroughs and three districts (Dutch: *stadsdelen*), three of which are under construction.
[src:almere/almere] Almere has an oceanic climate characterized by mild to cool winters, and warm summers with fair precipitation year-round.
[src:almere/almere] On 19 May 2004, at the instigation of Kees Kousemaker, owner of the Amsterdam comics store Lambiek, the first buildings of the *Stripheldenbuurt* were inaugurated in Almere.
[src:almere/almere] This is a district where all street names are named after famous comics characters and cartoonists.
[src:almere/almere] Almere is the home of football team Almere City FC, American football team FlevoPhantoms, and the home of professional basketball team the Almere Sailors.
[src:almere/almere] The traffic infrastructure in Almere is recognisable because of its separate infrastructure for cycles (which, in most cases, have separate cycle paths), cars and buses (the buses drive on a separate bus lane in most parts of the city).
[src:almere/almere] Almere is connected to the motorways A6 and A27.
[src:almere/almere] In 1987 Almere was connected to the national railway system (see NS) with the fully completed Flevolijn which connected Weesp to Lelystad Centrum.
[src:almere/almere] A seasonal-use station, Almere Strand, was set up for certain events, such as Libelle Zomerweek.
[src:almere/almere] The station was made up of iron platforms.
[src:almere/almere] It was opened in May 1996 under the name *Muiderzand*.
[src:almere/almere] The station was closed after June 1996 but re-opened in June 1999 under the name *Muiderstrand* and closed again in July 1999.
[src:almere/almere] It re-opened again in 2001 under the name *Almere Strand* as an official seasonal-use station, meaning it was now open certain seasons every year.
[src:almere/almere] Because of the rapid development of the adjacent borough Almere Poort, it was decided to open an official station there (see Almere Poort), thus making the station of Almere Strand obsolete.
[src:almere/almere] Almere Poort station opened on December 9, 2012.
[src:almere/almere] Therefore, Almere Strand station was officially closed just after the summer of 2012 and its iron platforms were torn down in the weekend of October 6–7, 2012.
[src:almere/almere] There are no remains of the station, although passengers can still see where the platforms once stood from the windows of Flevolijn trains.
[src:almere/almere] In Almere there are 10 bus lines which service the urban area.
[src:almere/almere] Monday to Friday, most city buses run about every 5 minutes (10 times every hour) during daytime hours.
[src:almere/almere] Saturdays, only a few city bus lines run every 7.5 minutes during daytime hours; most of them run every 12–15 minutes.
[src:almere/almere] Sunday, most of the city buses run every 15 minutes (with some buses running extra runs during certain hours) and M6 which only runs every 30 minutes.
[src:almere/almere] There are a few overnight bus lines (Mon-Sat nights only): N21, N22 and N23.
[src:almere/almere] They run under the Keolis internal name nightGo (but are operated by R-net branded regional buses).
[src:almere/almere] The bus company running almost all buses is Keolis Netherlands.
[src:almere/almere] Local buses (city buses) run under the name allGo.
[src:almere/almere] In the buses one can use the national transportation chipcard (smart card), subscriptions or one can buy bus tickets of allGo in the bus or at TVM's (the latter only Downtown).
[src:almere/almere] Besides the local bus lines, there are regional and rush hour bus lines to towns and cities in the area.
[src:almere/almere] Since April 2012, there was a rush hour route, 150, to Utrecht which connected Almere directly with the University Area of Utrecht called De Uithof.
[src:almere/almere] (This was previously done by former bus line 295).
[src:almere/almere] Due to budget cuts, line 150 was scrapped on July 9, 2016.
